"""
mkt-christ | Leviticus 14-15 | Christological commentary
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-leviticus-14-15.py

Ch 14: Cleansing ritual for healed skin disease (tsara'at). The two-bird rite
types death+resurrection; the priest going OUT to the leper types the incarnation;
blood+oil on ear/thumb/toe recapitulates priestly ordination (Lev 8:23-24), so the
cleansed person is re-consecrated as a priest — fulfilled in the royal priesthood
(1 Pet 2:9). The poor person's provision (doves) matches Mary+Joseph's offering
at Jesus' presentation (Luke 2:24).

Ch 15: Bodily-discharge laws. The hemorrhaging woman of Mark 5:25-34 / Luke 8:43-48
lived under 15:25-27 for 12 years; her touch of Jesus reverses the impurity-flow
direction, making this passage the paradigm case for how Christ's holiness defeats
uncleanness. Purpose clause 15:31 grounds the whole system: the tabernacle's
dangerous holiness is resolved in Christ, who tabernacles IN believers (1 Cor 6:19).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent


def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}


def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")


def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


LEVITICUS = {
    "14": {
        "1": "<p>The LORD's speech to Moses initiates the restoration ritual. This is not merely hygienic law but theological procedure: the healed person must be formally readmitted to the covenant community by priestly action. Christ is the Great High Priest (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 4:14'>Heb 4:14</a>) who administers the final, definitive cleansing for every sinner restored to God.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The healed leper is <em>brought to the priest</em> — the initiative lies with those bringing him, and he is passive, having been restored. The once-excluded person now re-enters the process of re-admission. Christ receives all who come to him bearing the evidence of God's healing work (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 11:28'>Matt 11:28</a>).</p>",
        "3": "<p>The priest goes <em>outside the camp</em> to examine. This is the structural surprise: holiness moves toward uncleanness, not the reverse. The priest bears the risk of contact. Jesus, the true Priest, consistently crossed this boundary — going to lepers (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 8:2-3'>Matt 8:2-3</a>), the graveyard (<a class='ref' data-ref='Mark 5:1-2'>Mark 5:1-2</a>), and ultimately outside the holy city to die (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 13:12'>Heb 13:12</a>).</p>",
        "4": "<p>Two living clean birds, cedar wood, crimson yarn, and hyssop are assembled. The cluster — especially hyssop — appears at the Passover blood application (<a class='ref' data-ref='Exod 12:22'>Exod 12:22</a>), in David's penitential prayer (<a class='ref' data-ref='Ps 51:7'>Ps 51:7</a>), and at the cross (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 19:29'>John 19:29</a>). The crimson yarn echoes Isaiah's scarlet-to-white promise (<a class='ref' data-ref='Isa 1:18'>Isa 1:18</a>).</p>",
        "5": "<p>One bird is slaughtered over fresh running water in a clay pot. The blood mingles with living water — a combination echoed in John's report of blood and water at the piercing of Jesus' side (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 19:34'>John 19:34</a>), which the Fathers read as the source of baptism and Eucharist.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The living bird, cedar wood, crimson yarn, and hyssop are all dipped together into the blood of the slaughtered bird. The living is immersed in the death of its counterpart — a baptism into death. This foreshadows baptism into Christ's death (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rom 6:3-4'>Rom 6:3-4</a>) as the mechanism of cleansing and new life.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The blood is sprinkled seven times on the person — completeness of atonement — and then the priest declares <em>he is clean</em> and releases the living bird. The released bird carries the blood into the open field: a type of resurrection and ascension, the risen Christ applying his blood in the heavenly sanctuary (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 9:24'>Heb 9:24</a>).</p>",
        "8": "<p>The restored person washes clothes, shaves all hair, and bathes — a comprehensive physical reset. He may return inside the camp but must remain outside his tent seven days. The seven-day waiting period mirrors the Sabbath week, preparing for the eighth-day new-creation entry into full worship before God.</p>",
        "9": "<p>On the seventh day all hair is shaved — head, beard, eyebrows. The radical removal of every natural covering strips the person to bare creaturely vulnerability before God. Christ entered creation stripped of divine prerogative (<a class='ref' data-ref='Phil 2:7'>Phil 2:7</a>), and the believer stripped of self-righteousness is clothed in him (<a class='ref' data-ref='Gal 3:27'>Gal 3:27</a>).</p>",
        "10": "<p>On the eighth day: two unblemished male lambs, one unblemished ewe, grain, and oil. The eighth day is the first day of a new week — resurrection day. Every eighth-day ordinance in Leviticus (ordination, firstborn presentation) points to the new creation inaugurated by Christ's resurrection on the first day of the week (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 20:1'>John 20:1</a>).</p>",
        "11": "<p>The priest presents the cleansed man and his offerings <em>before the LORD at the entrance of the tent of meeting</em>. The priest acts as intercessor, bringing the restored person into God's presence — an exact figure of Christ's priestly work: <em>he always lives to make intercession for them</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 7:25'>Heb 7:25</a>), presenting the redeemed before the Father.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The guilt offering (asham) lamb is presented with the log of oil as a wave offering. The asham atones for specific trespass — the guilt of having been excluded from worship and possibly of religious violations during that time. Christ's sacrifice addresses not only the act of sin but the accumulated guilt of people living in varying degrees of spiritual exile.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The asham lamb is slaughtered in the holy place where the sin offering and burnt offering are slaughtered — it belongs to the priest, most holy. Christ, as the one who offered himself, is simultaneously priest and victim, the most holy sacrifice offered in the true holy place (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 9:11-12'>Heb 9:11-12</a>).</p>",
        "14": "<p>Blood from the guilt offering is placed on the lobe of the right ear, the thumb of the right hand, and the big toe of the right foot. This is identical to the consecration of Aaron and his sons in Lev 8:23-24. The cleansed leper receives the same anointing as a priest — restored not merely to layperson status but to priestly dignity. In Christ, <em>you are a royal priesthood</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Pet 2:9'>1 Pet 2:9</a>).</p>",
        "15": "<p>The priest takes from the log of oil. Oil throughout the sacrificial system signifies the Spirit's anointing: prophets, priests, and kings are anointed with oil. The cleansed person receives the Spirit's imprint on the same three points as the blood: hearing (right ear), working (right hand), walking (right foot) — the whole direction of life consecrated to God.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The priest sprinkles oil seven times before the LORD. Seven sprinklings of oil toward the sanctuary recalls the sprinklings before the veil in Yom Kippur (Lev 16:14-19). The Spirit given to Christ without measure (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 3:34'>John 3:34</a>) is the source of the sevenfold fullness he bestows on his people.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Oil is applied to the right ear lobe, right thumb, and right big toe — on top of the blood. Blood then oil: atonement first, then consecration. The order matters: justification (blood applied) precedes sanctification (Spirit's oil applied). The two cannot be reversed; the anointed life flows from the atoned-for life.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The remaining oil is poured on the head of the person being cleansed. The anointing of the head recalls Samuel anointing David king (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Sam 16:13'>1 Sam 16:13</a>). The cleansed leper is anointed from head to toe — a complete kingly and priestly consecration. <em>Christ</em> means <em>the Anointed One</em>; his anointing is the prototype of all anointing of his people.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The priest offers the sin offering (ḥatta't) for the uncleanness. Atonement is made before the full restoration is complete. The sequence — guilt offering, anointing, sin offering, burnt offering — shows that restoration is multi-dimensional: trespass, status, sin, and total consecration are each addressed. Christ's single offering addresses all these dimensions (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 10:14'>Heb 10:14</a>).</p>",
        "20": "<p>After the burnt offering, the priest makes atonement and the person is clean. The word <em>clean</em> (tahor) marks the completed status — a declarative verdict. Justification is this priestly declaration based on the offerings. Christ's <em>It is finished</em> is the final priestly declaration of this kind (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 19:30'>John 19:30</a>).</p>",
        "21": "<p>If the person is poor and cannot afford two lambs, one lamb suffices. The Torah's graduated provision ensures that wealth does not determine access to cleansing. Mary and Joseph brought the poor person's option — two turtledoves — at Jesus' presentation (<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 2:24'>Luke 2:24</a>), showing that Christ was born under the law's poverty provision, in solidarity with those at the economic margins.</p>",
        "22": "<p>Two turtledoves or two young pigeons — one as sin offering, one as burnt offering — replace the two lambs of the standard rite. The dove is the Spirit's symbol (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 3:16'>Matt 3:16</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='John 1:32'>John 1:32</a>); the same creatures that appear at Jesus' baptism are the offering of those too poor for lambs — Christ identified with both symbols.</p>",
        "23": "<p>On the eighth day he brings them to the priest. The eight-day pattern unifies the cleansed leper's restoration with the ordination week (Lev 8-9), circumcision (Gen 17:12), and the resurrection. The eighth day is the day beyond the Sabbath rest — new creation, not merely renewed creation.</p>",
        "24": "<p>The priest waves the guilt-offering lamb and the oil before the LORD as a wave offering — toward God and back. The wave offering enacts priestly intercession: the offering is presented to God who returns its benefit to the worshiper. Christ's intercession follows this pattern: he presents himself to the Father on behalf of the redeemed (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 9:24'>Heb 9:24</a>).</p>",
        "25": "<p>For the poor person's guilt offering, blood is applied to the ear, thumb, and big toe as before. The same triple anointing regardless of the offering tier: wealth determines the animal, but the form of consecration is identical. In Christ there is no poor/rich distinction in status before God (<a class='ref' data-ref='Gal 3:28'>Gal 3:28</a>); all receive the same priestly anointing.</p>",
        "26": "<p>The priest pours oil into his own left palm — making himself the vessel of the Spirit's anointing, the instrument through which God's grace is administered. The incarnation is the supreme instance of this: God making human flesh the instrument of divine grace bestowed on the unclean.</p>",
        "27": "<p>Seven sprinklings of oil before the LORD — the sevenfold completeness of Spirit. The seven-branched menorah in the tabernacle symbolizes the fullness of the Spirit's illuminating presence. The Messiah of Isa 11:2 receives the Spirit's sevenfold rest upon him, then distributes this same anointing to his cleansed people.</p>",
        "28": "<p>Oil on the ear, thumb, and toe — on top of the blood already applied. Blood first, oil second. This is the pattern of the Christian life: crucified with Christ first (<a class='ref' data-ref='Gal 2:20'>Gal 2:20</a>), then walking by the Spirit (<a class='ref' data-ref='Gal 5:25'>Gal 5:25</a>). Atonement is the foundation; consecration is the structure built on it.</p>",
        "29": "<p>The remaining oil is poured on the head to make atonement. The kipper root here carries the full weight of both covering and wiping away — the priest's act resolves the person's standing before God completely. The head-anointing completes the re-consecration from the ground up.</p>",
        "30": "<p>One turtledove or pigeon as sin offering, one as burnt offering. The two birds of the poor person's offering echo the two birds of the opening purification ritual (vv. 4-7): one dies, one lives. Death and life — the atonement pattern — runs through both the opening rite and the concluding sacrifices, a double signature of Christ's death and resurrection.</p>",
        "31": "<p>The priest makes atonement before the LORD for the one being cleansed. The phrase <em>before the LORD</em> (liphne YHWH) insists that the cleansing is relational, not merely ceremonial. The goal is restored standing in YHWH's presence. <em>We have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rom 5:1'>Rom 5:1</a>) — the access granted is relational restoration with the Person.</p>",
        "32": "<p>Summary of the law for the person with skin disease who cannot afford the standard offering. The Torah's compassionate provision ensures that no poverty can permanently exclude from cleansing and restoration. The gospel goes further: Christ's atonement costs the recipient nothing — the debt is entirely absorbed by the priest-victim himself.</p>",
        "33": "<p>God speaks to both Moses and Aaron together. The dual address signals that these house-disease laws require both prophetic proclamation (Moses) and priestly administration (Aaron). Christ holds both offices: the prophet who declares the word and the priest who applies the atonement for defiled structures.</p>",
        "34": "<p>When Israel enters Canaan, disease may appear even in the houses YHWH gives them. This is striking: YHWH himself may <em>put</em> a mark in a house. The land is not exempt from corruption even when it is the gift. Human fallenness pervades even the best of God's gifts in this age. The new creation will be a land with no disease in its structures (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 21:4'>Rev 21:4</a>).</p>",
        "35": "<p>The owner must report the suspected disease to the priest — not diagnose or dismiss it himself. The pattern of self-reporting to the priest reflects the conscience's proper role: to notice and bring to God what needs examination. The examination belongs to the priestly mediator, not to the owner. Christ alone is qualified to assess what is truly defiled.</p>",
        "36": "<p>The house is emptied before priestly examination so that its contents are not automatically defiled. Pastoral wisdom is embedded here: God does not want unnecessary collateral damage in diagnosing sin. Christ's purpose is to save, not to condemn (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 3:17'>John 3:17</a>); diagnosis does not require condemning everything associated with the defiled.</p>",
        "37": "<p>Greenish or reddish streaks set below the surface indicate the disease. The priest must look below the surface — what appears as mere discoloration may be a deep structural problem. Jesus discerned what was <em>in people</em> without being told (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 2:25'>John 2:25</a>); his diagnosis penetrates surface appearances to structural reality.</p>",
        "38": "<p>The priest leaves and quarantines the house for seven days — a period of confirmed assessment before final verdict. God's patience in judgment, his slowness to condemn definitively, is a consistent pastoral attribute. <em>The Lord is not slow to fulfill his promise... but is patient toward you</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='2 Pet 3:9'>2 Pet 3:9</a>).</p>",
        "39": "<p>The priest returns on the seventh day: if the marks have spread, more action is required. Persistence of the problem demands response. Christ, as the ongoing Shepherd-Priest, meets his people across time in their progression or regression, not merely at the initial moment of cleansing.</p>",
        "40": "<p>The diseased stones are torn out and thrown outside the city to an unclean place. Radical removal of infected material is required before restoration can proceed. Jesus taught that radical self-surgery is sometimes necessary (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 5:29-30'>Matt 5:29-30</a>): if your eye causes you to sin, remove it. Localized excision to preserve the whole.</p>",
        "41": "<p>The house is scraped on the inside and the plaster is dumped outside the city — not merely the stones but the entire surface treatment must go. Thorough reformation is required: not cosmetic patching but structural renewal. New creation is not a cosmetic overlay but a fundamental rebuilding (<a class='ref' data-ref='2 Cor 5:17'>2 Cor 5:17</a>).</p>",
        "42": "<p>New stones and new plaster replace the removed material. After destruction comes reconstruction. The pattern of tearing down and rebuilding points forward to Christ's word about the temple: <em>Destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 2:19'>John 2:19</a>). Death and resurrection is the structural logic of all biblical renewal.</p>",
        "43": "<p>If the disease returns in the re-plastered house, the underlying problem was not resolved by the first intervention. This corresponds to warnings about sin that returns after partial repentance — the final state worse than the beginning (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 12:43-45'>Matt 12:43-45</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='2 Pet 2:20-22'>2 Pet 2:20-22</a>).</p>",
        "44": "<p>The spreading mark in the re-plastered house declares it malignant and unclean. The final verdict reflects not hasty condemnation but the outcome of exhausted opportunity for restoration. God's patience in the face of persistent, returning sin ultimately gives way to judgment.</p>",
        "45": "<p>The house is demolished completely and its materials carried outside the city to an unclean place. Total destruction is the only resolution for what cannot be purified. The eschatological judgment dismantles all that has been corrupted beyond recovery. But in Christ, even persons — not merely houses — receive new life from demolition (<a class='ref' data-ref='2 Cor 5:17'>2 Cor 5:17</a>).</p>",
        "46": "<p>Anyone who enters the quarantined house becomes unclean until evening. Uncleanness is communicable through the environment of sin. But Christ entered the unclean space of human existence without becoming unclean. His holiness was stronger than the environment's defilement (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 7:26'>Heb 7:26</a>).</p>",
        "47": "<p>Those who sleep or eat in the house must wash their clothes. The deepest engagement with the contaminated environment requires the most extensive cleansing. Washing garments through baptism (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 7:14'>Rev 7:14</a>) addresses the comprehensive defilement of a life lived in a fallen world.</p>",
        "48": "<p>If the disease has not spread after re-plastering, the priest declares the house clean. Good news is equally the priest's responsibility as bad news. The diagnostic function exists for both verdicts. Christ came not to condemn but to save (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 3:17'>John 3:17</a>); the priestly declaration of cleanness is the goal, not the condemnation.</p>",
        "49": "<p>For the house's purification: the same two birds, cedar wood, crimson yarn, hyssop as the leper's rite (v. 4). The house is treated with the same complete purification kit as the individual person. In Christ, <em>all things</em> are reconciled to God — not only persons but the whole created order (<a class='ref' data-ref='Col 1:20'>Col 1:20</a>).</p>",
        "50": "<p>One bird slaughtered over fresh water in a clay pot. The mingling of blood and living water initiates the cleansing of the house as it did for the individual. The material fabric of a place is renewed by the same atoning mechanism as a person — blood and water, pointing again to the twin sacraments flowing from Christ's side (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 19:34'>John 19:34</a>).</p>",
        "51": "<p>Cedar wood, hyssop, crimson yarn, and the living bird are dipped in the blood and sprinkled on the house seven times. Seven-fold sprinkling of blood on a structure mirrors the Yom Kippur sprinkling before the mercy seat. The house receives what the holy of holies receives — a complete, comprehensive atonement brought within the scope of Christ's single offering.</p>",
        "52": "<p>The house is purified with the blood of the slaughtered bird, fresh water, the living bird, cedar wood, hyssop, and crimson yarn — the full purification kit deployed completely. No element is omitted. Christ's atoning work is not partial or selective; every element of his life, death, and resurrection bears on the comprehensive purification of his people and their world.</p>",
        "53": "<p>The living bird is released into the open field outside the city. As in the leper's rite (v. 7), the blood-dipped living bird carries the atonement outward and upward. Christ's resurrection and ascension are this final release — the blood-bearing life of the risen Lord brought into the open field of heaven, where he makes continual intercession (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 7:25'>Heb 7:25</a>).</p>",
        "54": "<p>The phrase <em>this is the law</em> begins a comprehensive summary. The teaching function of the purity system is underscored: these laws exist not merely for sanitary management but for theological instruction about uncleanness, its diagnosis, and its cure. The entire system finds its telos in Christ, who is the end (goal) of the law (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rom 10:4'>Rom 10:4</a>).</p>",
        "55": "<p>Disease in a garment and in a house are included in the comprehensive purification law. The reach of the law extends beyond bodily conditions to the artifacts and structures of human life. In Christ, the whole material world of human habitation comes under the stewardship and eventual renewal of his atoning work (<a class='ref' data-ref='Col 1:20'>Col 1:20</a>).</p>",
        "56": "<p>Swelling, scab, and bright spot — the diagnostic categories of ch. 13 — are included in the closing summary. No variety of human affliction falls outside the system's coverage. Christ's atonement covers every category and condition: <em>he is the propitiation for our sins, and not for ours only but also for the sins of the whole world</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 John 2:2'>1 John 2:2</a>).</p>",
        "57": "<p><em>To teach when something is unclean and when it is clean</em> — the pedagogical function is stated explicitly. The entire skin-disease regulation exists to form a people who know the difference between the holy and the common. This discernment faculty is now administered by the Spirit of holiness, who convicts of sin and righteousness and judgment (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 16:8'>John 16:8</a>) and is the permanent teacher within the community of the cleansed.</p>",
    },
    "15": {
        "1": "<p>The LORD speaks to both Moses and Aaron together, as in 14:33. The dual address signals that these discharge laws require both prophetic proclamation (Moses) and priestly administration (Aaron). Christ holds both offices: the prophet who declares the word and the priest who applies the atonement.</p>",
        "2": "<p>A man with a bodily discharge (zav — likely a chronic genital condition) is made unclean <em>by his discharge</em>. The uncleanness radiates from the body outward. This is the opposite direction from Christ's holiness, which radiates from his person outward to cleanse those he touches (<a class='ref' data-ref='Mark 1:41'>Mark 1:41</a>). The gospel inverts the contamination logic of the fall.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Whether the body lets the discharge flow or is blocked, the man is unclean. The uncleanness is tied to the condition itself, not to its visibility or activity at any given moment. Christ's cleansing addresses the underlying condition — not just its outward manifestations. He heals the source, not merely the symptoms.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Every bed the man with the discharge lies on becomes unclean. The contamination extends to his resting places — wherever he seeks rest becomes defiled. In Christ, the rest promised to the weary is clean and cleansing: <em>Come to me all who are weary... and I will give you rest</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 11:28-29'>Matt 11:28-29</a>).</p>",
        "5": "<p>Touching the bed requires washing clothes and bathing — unclean until evening. The spreading uncleanness through touch establishes the logic that the hemorrhaging woman (Mark 5:25-34) navigated: she had to touch something, knowing her condition spread uncleanness to whatever she touched. Her desperation in reaching for Jesus was an act of faith precisely because she understood the system she was violating.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Sitting where the man sat also transmits uncleanness. Social proximity, shared space, ordinary human contact — all become vectors of impurity. The discharge laws give texture to the social exclusion Paul describes as the pre-conversion state: <em>excluded from the commonwealth of Israel... having no hope and without God</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 2:12'>Eph 2:12</a>).</p>",
        "7": "<p>Touching the body of the man with the discharge spreads uncleanness. Direct contact is the primary transmission mechanism. Jesus accepted direct contact from the unclean — laying hands on lepers, touching the bier of the dead, being touched by the hemorrhaging woman — without the impurity vector working on him. His touch did not receive uncleanness; it transmitted cleanness.</p>",
        "8": "<p>If the man spits on a clean person, the clean person becomes unclean. Spitting is among the most intimate forms of bodily contact — associated with contempt and the transmission of what is internal to the external world. At his trial, Jesus was spat upon (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 26:67'>Matt 26:67</a>); he received the defilement of human contempt without being defiled by it.</p>",
        "9": "<p>Every saddle the man with the discharge rides on is unclean — his mode of transportation through the world becomes a source of spreading impurity. In Christ, the believer's journey through the world is covered: <em>your life is hidden with Christ in God</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='Col 3:3'>Col 3:3</a>).</p>",
        "10": "<p>Whatever was beneath him spreads uncleanness; carrying it requires washing. In Christ, he bore the weight of human uncleanness himself — taking on the contamination so that those who were beneath him might be raised with him (<a class='ref' data-ref='Col 2:12'>Col 2:12</a>).</p>",
        "11": "<p>The man who touches the zav without having rinsed his hands becomes unclean. Even casual contact requires attention to preparedness. The Spirit's work in the believer cultivates exactly this kind of attentiveness to holiness and its conditions — a transformed conscience that monitors one's approach to the holy.</p>",
        "12": "<p>A clay vessel touched by the zav must be broken; a wooden vessel is merely rinsed. Clay cannot be purified by washing — it must be destroyed. Paul uses the clay vessel image for human bodies as containers of divine treasure (<a class='ref' data-ref='2 Cor 4:7'>2 Cor 4:7</a>). The old self — the clay pot shaped by the fall — must be broken, not merely rinsed; hence the dying and rising of baptism, not mere reformation.</p>",
        "13": "<p>When the discharge ceases, the man counts seven days, washes his clothes, bathes in running water, and is clean. The counting of seven days mirrors the creation week — a period of confirmed healing before restoration. Running water (mayim ḥayyim, <em>living water</em>) is the medium of cleansing — the same phrase Jesus uses for the Spirit (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 4:10-11'>John 4:10-11</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='John 7:38'>John 7:38</a>).</p>",
        "14": "<p>On the eighth day, two turtledoves or two young pigeons are brought before the LORD at the tent of meeting. The same offering used for the poor leper's cleansing (14:22). The dove — Spirit symbol — completes both rites of restoration. Christ's baptism, marked by the Spirit's descent as a dove, inaugurates his ministry of restoring all who bear the marks of bodily and spiritual discharge.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The priest offers one bird as a sin offering and one as a burnt offering. Sin (the condition of uncleanness) and total dedication (the restored person's self-giving to God) are the two aspects of restoration. Christ both atones for sin and consecrates his people as a living sacrifice (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rom 12:1'>Rom 12:1</a>) in total dedication to God.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Seminal emission renders a man unclean until evening — a mild impurity resolved by nightfall. It acknowledges that even the most fundamental created gift of fertility participates in the impurity system. Christ's incarnation did not carry this impurity: born of a virgin (<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 1:35'>Luke 1:35</a>), he entered the human condition without this transmission from Adam.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Any garment or leather with seminal emission must be washed — unclean until evening. The material world that contacts human physicality participates in its impurity. The comprehensive renewal in Christ extends to the physical: the resurrection of the body is the final answer to all such conditions, when the redeemed body no longer operates under the law of impurity.</p>",
        "18": "<p>Conjugal intimacy creates temporary impurity that resolves by evening. The fall has marked even the good gift of sexuality with the shadow of uncleanness. The marriage relationship is the arena Christ chooses to illustrate his union with the church (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 5:25-27'>Eph 5:25-27</a>), a union in which he presents the bride <em>without spot or wrinkle... holy and without blemish</em>.</p>",
        "19": "<p>A woman in her menstrual period (niddah) is unclean for seven days; whoever touches her is unclean until evening. The monthly cycle marks the female body with a recurring rhythm of impurity-and-restoration. Mary bore Jesus during the months when her own body was the site of God's incarnation — the holy and the ordinary creaturely rhythm intertwined in the one pregnancy that changes all of history.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Everything she lies on or sits on during the niddah period is unclean. As with the zav, the environment participates in the impurity. The thoroughgoing reach of the laws reflects how deeply uncleanness pervades ordinary structures of life. The coming of God's kingdom into these ordinary spaces is the good news: Christ comes into the niddah world, not away from it.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Touching her bed spreads uncleanness. The spreading-by-contact principle applies uniformly across all discharge categories. The consistency of the system teaches that no area of ordinary life is exempt from the human condition. The gospel's reach must be equally consistent: Christ's cleansing is not limited to spiritual matters but extends into the physical and relational dimensions these laws govern.</p>",
        "22": "<p>Touching anything she sat on spreads uncleanness. The surfaces of ordinary life — sitting places, resting places — are where the laws of uncleanness apply most concretely. Jesus' ministry was full of precisely these ordinary contacts: meals at people's homes, sitting in boats, touching ordinary people in ordinary places. His holiness engaged, rather than avoided, the ordinary contaminated world.</p>",
        "23": "<p>Whether on the bed or on anything she sat on — touching it brings uncleanness. The repetition reinforces comprehensiveness. No loophole exists. Similarly, the problem of human uncleanness before God admits no loophole: <em>all have sinned</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rom 3:23'>Rom 3:23</a>); the only solution is atonement, not navigation around the system.</p>",
        "24": "<p>If a man sleeps with a woman during her menstrual period, he becomes unclean for seven days. The impurity of her state is transferred to the man who fully shares her condition through marital union. A full creation-week-length period of exclusion from worship — a sign of how far the created order has been affected by the fall, reaching even into its most intimate goods.</p>",
        "25": "<p>A woman with a chronic discharge of blood outside her normal cycle is in the niddah state for as long as the discharge continues. This is the exact condition of the woman in <a class='ref' data-ref='Mark 5:25-34'>Mark 5:25-34</a> and <a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 8:43-48'>Luke 8:43-48</a>, who had suffered this for twelve years — perpetually unclean, perpetually excluded from normal communal and worship life.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Her bed during the discharge days is unclean as her menstrual bed; everything she sits on is unclean. For twelve years, every bed and every seat the hemorrhaging woman used was rendered unclean. The social isolation this implies is comprehensive: she could not sit in the synagogue, recline at meals, or rest in her household without spreading impurity. Her twelve-year exile was a living death.</p>",
        "27": "<p>Whoever touches these things becomes unclean. The woman of Mark 5 knew the system. She pressed through the crowd to touch Jesus — knowing she would spread uncleanness to everyone she brushed against, knowing she was violating the law's intent. Her desperation and faith drove her to the one place where she believed the impurity-logic might be reversed. And she was right: the power went from him to her (<a class='ref' data-ref='Mark 5:30'>Mark 5:30</a>).</p>",
        "28": "<p>When the discharge stops, she counts seven clean days and then is clean. After twelve years of perpetual discharge, the very moment of stopping would have inaugurated this seven-day count for the woman Jesus healed. Her <em>immediate</em> healing (<a class='ref' data-ref='Mark 5:29'>Mark 5:29</a>) launched her restoration; Jesus' declaration <em>your faith has made you well</em> (<a class='ref' data-ref='Mark 5:34'>Mark 5:34</a>) anticipates and ratifies the full restoration the law's process would complete.</p>",
        "29": "<p>On the eighth day she brings two turtledoves or two young pigeons to the priest. The same eighth-day offering as the cleansed male zav (v. 14). Male and female receive identical restoration procedure. There is no gendered hierarchy in the means of atonement — both are restored through the same priestly intercession and the same dove sacrifice.</p>",
        "30": "<p>One dove as sin offering, one as burnt offering; the priest makes atonement before the LORD. The complete restoration formula: sin addressed (ḥatta't), total dedication given (olah), atonement made. The hemorrhaging woman's restoration in Christ is this complete: not partial healing but full atonement and reconstitution as a daughter of Abraham (<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 13:16'>Luke 13:16</a>).</p>",
        "31": "<p><em>You shall keep the people of Israel separate from their uncleanness, lest they die in their uncleanness by defiling my tabernacle that is in their midst.</em> The purpose clause of all purity law: YHWH's tabernacle presence is simultaneously the greatest gift and the gravest danger. In Christ, this danger is permanently resolved: God no longer merely tabernacles <em>among</em> us but <em>in</em> us (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Cor 6:19'>1 Cor 6:19</a>), having absorbed the deadly collision of holiness and uncleanness in the cross.</p>",
        "32": "<p>This is the law for the man with a discharge, the man who has a seminal emission and becomes unclean by it. The masculine summary closes the male discharge laws (vv. 2-18). Christ, assuming full human embodiment, entered this full range of creaturely experience without incurring any of its impurity — and then took the penalty for all of it (<a class='ref' data-ref='2 Cor 5:21'>2 Cor 5:21</a>).</p>",
        "33": "<p>Summary of all discharge categories: the woman in menstrual separation, the man or woman with any discharge, the man who lies with an unclean woman. The closing summary universalizes: all human beings across all categories of bodily discharge need priestly atonement for restoration to God's presence. The comprehensive need finds comprehensive answer in Christ, the one sacrifice that covers all categories and all persons for all time (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 10:12'>Heb 10:12</a>).</p>",
    },
}


def main():
    data = load_comm("mkt-christ", "leviticus")
    merge_comm(data, LEVITICUS)
    save_comm("mkt-christ", "leviticus", data)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
